RcmdrPlugin.biostat 0.0.60

R Commander Plug-in for Basic Data Management and Analysis Tasks

RcmdrPlugin.biostat is an Rcmdr plug-in for the most common data wrangling, visualization and analysis tasks that uses tidyverse family functions as well as functions from other packages. The documentation is available at gegznav.github.io/RcmdrPlugin.biostat.

Install the package

Before you begin installation or updating, make sure that only a single R/RStudio session is running and restart current R session (to unload the packages). It is also recommended to close current RStudio project, if you use one.

To install the development version of the package from “GitHub”:

# Install required packages
if (!require("remotes"))  install.packages("remotes")

# Install RcmdrPlugin.biostat
remotes::install_github("GegznaV/RcmdrPlugin.biostat", upgrade = TRUE)

In case you face installation issues, follow the instructions in the error message. You may also try removing upgrade = TRUE and manually choose the packages to update. It is always recommended to restart R session before the next installation too.

NOTE: the most common installation issue is related to R package rlang. Usually, you have to delete the indicated “00LOCK” directory, restart current R session and try to install again.

Previous versions

If you need a previous version of the package, find section “Previous versions of RcmdrPlugin.biostat” below.

Load the plug-in correctly

NOTE: At least Rcmdr version 2.6-2 is required.

Note for Mac users only

For Mac users, there at least 2 things to pay attention to:

1) On Mac, R Commander opens only if XQuartz is opened. So, first step of using R Commander is to make sure that XQuartz is opened. More information on “Installing R Commander for Mac users”.

2) Some Mac users also report, that it is impossible to switch between languages while R Commander is running. This means, that some users might not use numbers if in the chosen language the same keys mean some non-English letters. Because of this, it is recommended to choose an appropriate language (usually English) before opening R/RStudio.

Load by using a script

You may load the package RcmdrPlugin.biostat programmatically or by using menus:

  • Option 1. Run code:

    library(RcmdrPlugin.biostat)
restart_commander()

    In a pop-up window, agree to restart.

  • Option 2. Run code:

    options(Rcmdr = list(plugins = "RcmdrPlugin.biostat", console.output = FALSE))
library(Rcmdr)

  • Option 3: use RStudio and R Commander menus (see section “Load by using menus”).

  • Next, turn on BioStat mode (see section “Turn on BioStat (green) mode”).

Load by using menus

  1. Load package Rcmdr by either selecting Rcmdr in RStudio „Packages“ menu:

    Or by using R code:

    library(Rcmdr)

    Wait until R Commander window opens.

  2. Then load the plug-in (as well as the other necessary plug-ins) through Tools → Load Rcmdr plug-in(s) in the R Commander menu bar.

    If you need more than one plug-in to be loaded, hold Ctrl key while selecting the plug-ins. To load the plug-ins, R Commander must restart.

NOTE: be aware that some plug-ins are incompatible one to the other and some combinations of plug-ins may break R Commander (e.g., “RcmdrPlugin.EZR” and “RcmdrPlugin.EZR.as.menu”). In this kind of situations, you should restart R session and try the other combination of plugins.

NOTE: if “RcmdrPlugin.biostat” is not between the options of Plugins, it means that the plugin is already chosen but not included in the menus of R Commander. This means that you should restart the R Commander by using function restart_commander().


  1. When RcmdrPlugin.biostat is loaded, you can access its functionality through BioStat'20 menu in the menu bar:

Turn on BioStat (green) mode

A more convenient way to use the plug-in is to turn on the BioStat mode. This mode uses the green icon instead of the blue one.


In this mode, additional buttons, which enable access to the most common functions, are added below the menu bar:

NOTE: if active dataset is not selected, some buttons are inactive.


Close BioStat mode

To close this mode, simply restart the R Commander:

  • R Commander menu bar → BioStat’20 → Session → Restart R Commander

You may use the following command as well:

restart_commander()

The other useful packages

Other useful Rcmdr plug-ins:

  1. RcmdrPlugin.EZR.as.menu – an R Commander plugin for the most common statistical analyses (functionality is the same as in RcmdrPlugin.EZR, except that RcmdrPlugin.EZR.as.menu creates a separate “EZR” menu in a menu bar and does not reorganize the original Rcmdr menus in the menu bar);
  2. RcmdrPlugin.KMggplot2 – an R Commander plugin for ggplot2 graphics.

To install these packages, use the following code:

# RcmdrPlugin.EZR.as.menu
remotes::install_github("GegznaV/RcmdrPlugin.EZR", ref = "ezr_as_menu")

# RcmdrPlugin.KMggplot2
install.packages("RcmdrPlugin.KMggplot2")

After the packages are installed, you can load them programmatically:

options(Rcmdr = list(
  plugins = c(
    "RcmdrPlugin.KMggplot2",
    "RcmdrPlugin.EZR.as.menu",
    "RcmdrPlugin.biostat",
    NULL
  ), 
  console.output = FALSE
))

library(Rcmdr)

If package Rcmdr is loaded and R Commander window is closed, instead of library(Rcmdr) use:

Commander()

Important

Some functions in the package are based on and modified from functions in packages Rcmdr, and RcmdrPlugin.EZR. All of those packages are under GPL-2/GPL-3 license.

Previous versions of RcmdrPlugin.biostat

If you need a previous version of RcmdrPlugin.biostat, you can install them from GitHub:

  • BioStat’19 (Autumn 2019):

    remotes::install_github("GegznaV/RcmdrPlugin.biostat", ref = "biostat19r")

    (r – lith. “ruduo”)

  • BioStat’19 (Spring 2019):

    remotes::install_github("GegznaV/RcmdrPlugin.biostat", ref = "biostat19")

  • BioStat’18 (2018):

    remotes::install_github("GegznaV/RcmdrPlugin.biostat", ref = "biostat18")

NOTE: these versions are no longer maintained and may not work properly.
